@startuml Copy_Summary
!theme plain

title Shallow vs Deep Copy Summary

card ShallowCopy [
  **Shallow Copy:**
  Copies pointer values
  Multiple objects point to same memory
  Double delete when destructed
  CRASH or undefined behavior
  
  Default compiler behavior
  for classes with pointers
]

card DeepCopy [
  **Deep Copy:**
  Creates new memory
  Copies actual data
  Each object owns its memory
  Safe destruction
  
  Must implement manually
  Copy constructor
  Copy assignment operator
]

card Modern [
  **Modern C++ (Best):**
  Use smart pointers
  unique_ptr, shared_ptr
  vector, string
  
  Automatic deep copy
  No manual memory management
  Compiler does it right
]

ShallowCopy -down-> DeepCopy : Fix with
DeepCopy -down-> Modern : Better: Use

note bottom
  **Key Points:**
  - Shallow copy = copy pointers (dangerous)
  - Deep copy = copy data (safe but manual)
  - Modern C++ = use smart pointers (best)
  
  **This connects to virtual destructor:**
  All need proper destruction through
  base pointers - hence virtual destructor!
end note

@enduml